explanation: To check the MISRA rule about pointer const-qualification for OS_mv we must know the parameter types of the functions to which src and dest are passed. If any callee is declared to take a non-const char * then passing const char * would discard const and violate the rule. Therefore you need: 1) OS_rename prototype — to determine whether its parameters are const-qualified (e.g. const char *src, const char *dest) or plain char *. 2) OS_cp prototype — to determine the const-qualification of its source/destination parameters. 3) OS_remove prototype — to determine whether passing src (const char *) to it discards const. Additionally include type/constant definitions used in the function signature and return handling: 4) int32 typedef/definition — to ensure the function signature matches the actual type (not directly about const pointers but required for complete analysis). 5) OS_SUCCESS macro/enum/constant — to interpret the return-value comparisons (not about pointer constness but required context).
